":"1273–Overleden","1268":"1268","1289":"1289","1288":"1288","1342":"1342","1364":"1364","1320":"1320","1273":"1273","1361":"1361","1309":"1309","Shirwell, Barnstaple, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shirwell, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Shirwell, Barnstaple, Devonshire, England":"Shirwell, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1289–1364":"1289–1364","1268–Male":"1268–Deceased","1320–1361":"1320–1361","1288–1364":"1288–1364","1309–1342":"1309–1342","1273–Female":"1273–Deceased","1268":"1268","1289":"1289","1288":"1288","1342":"1342","1364":"1364","1320":"1320","1273":"1273","1361":"1361","1309":"1309","Shirwell, Barnstaple, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shirwell, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Shirwell, Barnstaple, Devonshire, England":"Shirwell, Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Beaumont","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Gilles, Gaetan, Honore, Jacques, Jean-Guy, Marcel.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of the five places in Normandy or several others elsewhere in France so named. The placename comes from Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>mont</i> ‘hill’. There are also places in England so named under Norman influence in Cumberland, Lancashire, and Essex, the last of which changed its name in the 12th century from <i>Fulepet</i> ‘foul pit’ to <i>Bealmont</i> ‘beautiful hill’; these may also have given rise to the surname. The surname is now widespread throughout England, but most common in Yorkshire. Compare   Belmont  .","History: Many English bearers of this surname are descended from Henry de Beaumont (died 1340), who came to England from France as a soldier, serving Kings Edward I, II, and III of England. He acquired the earldom of Buchan in Scotland by marriage. — Many American bearers of this surname are descendants of John Beaumont (1612–47), who came to North America from England in 1630. William Beaumont came from England to Cambridge MA in 1635 and subsequently moved to CT."],"variants":[{"name":"Bement","meanings":["English (Cambridgeshire): variant of   Beaumont  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Beeman","meanings":["English (Kent): occupational name for a beekeeper, from Middle English <i>bee-man</i> ‘bee-keeper’ (Old English <i>bēo</i> + <i>mann</i>).","English (Kent): variant of   Beaumont  .","Americanized form of German   Biemann   or of its Dutch cognate <b>Bieman</b>."]},{"name":"Belmont","meanings":["French and English (of Norman origin): variant of   Beaumont  .","Catalan: habitational name from the placename Bellmont ‘beautiful mountain’. Compare Spanish   Belmonte  ."]},{"name":"Baumunk","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Siegmund.","German: probably a Germanized form of a French Huguenot name <b>Beaumont</b> (see also   Beaumont  )."]},{"name":"Bayman","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire): variant of   Beaumont  .","Americanized form of German <b>Beumann</b> or <b>Bäumann</b>, variants of   Baumann  ."]}]},{"name":"Philip","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Greek name <i>Philippos</i>, meaning ‘lover of horses’, from <i>philein</i> ‘to love’ + <i>hippos</i> ‘horse’. This was popular in the classical period and since. It was the name of the father of  Alexander the Great . It was also the name of one of Christ's apostles, of a deacon ordained by the apostles after the death of Christ, and of several other early saints.  See also  Philippa ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Philip De Beaumont was born in 1289, in Shirwell, Devon, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Richard Beaumont, was 21 and his mother, Elizabeth Hall, was 16. He had at least 1 son with Ermegard de Punchardon, Heiress of Heanton Punchardon. He died in 1364, at the age of 75."},"et":{"1289–1364":"1289–1364","1268–Male":"1268–Surnud","1320–1361":"1320–1361","1288–1364":"1288–1364","1309–1342":"1309–1342","1273–Female":"1273–Surnud","1268":"1268","1289":"1289","1288":"1288","1342":"1342","1364":"1364","1320":"1320","1273":"1273","1361":"1361","1309":"1309","Shirwell, Barnstaple, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shirwell, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shirwell, Barnstaple, Devonshire, England":"Shirwell, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1289–1364":"1289–1364","1268–Male":"1268–Kuollut","1320–1361":"1320–1361","1288–1364":"1288–1364","1309–1342":"1309–1342","1273–Female":"1273–Kuollut","1268":"1268","1289":"1289","1288":"1288","1342":"1342","1364":"1364","1320":"1320","1273":"1273","1361":"1361","1309":"1309","Shirwell, Barnstaple, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shirwell, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Shirwell, Barnstaple, Devonshire, England":"Shirwell, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1289–1364":"1289–1364","1268–Male":"1268–Décédé","1320–1361":"1320–1361","1288–1364":"1288–1364","1309–1342":"1309–1342","1273–Female":"1273–Décédée","1268":"1268","1289":"1289","1288":"1288","1342":"1342","1364":"1364","1320":"1320","1273":"1273","1361":"1361","1309":"1309","Shirwell, Barnstaple, Devonshire